{"id":14880800,"mediaExerciseId":"5ecfed36-68ad-4525-8c50-a660705b95cf","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612275,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":85,"solutions":[{"id":5949935,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine the debt-equity ratio and equity multiplier for Queen, Inc.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before proceeding with the first requirement, let us define the total debt ratio.\n\nThe total debt ratio measures the company's assets financed by debt.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Total debt ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Total Debt}} {\\text{Total Assets}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/27/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/a5237fc45c243c76d3798407ba4967a7/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/27/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/a5237fc45c243c76d3798407ba4967a7/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Using the total-debt ratio, we can substitute the given ratio:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Total debt ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Total Debt}} {\\text{Total Assets}}\\\\ \\\\\n0.46& = \\dfrac{\\text{Total Debt}} {\\text{Total Debt + Total Equity}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nWe also know that total assets are the sum of total debt and total equity.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":269,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/27/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/d415defe1c145bfdf7a20f1754ab5cd1/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":137,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/27/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/d415defe1c145bfdf7a20f1754ab5cd1/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"By deriving the formula, debt-equity ratio can be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n0.46& =\n  \\dfrac{\\text{Total Debt}} {\\text{Total Debt + Total Equity}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\text{0.46 (Total Equity)}& = \\text{0.54 (Total Debt)}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":349,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/9dc69303551ba14e7649244fcf506a5a/lateximg_large.png","width":965},"regular":{"height":176,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/9dc69303551ba14e7649244fcf506a5a/lateximg.png","width":483}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we further proceed, let us also first define **debt-equity ratio**\n\n**Debt-equity ratio** measures a company's total debt against total equity.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Debt-equity ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Total Debt}} {\\text{Total Equity}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":222,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/4fb098bb3d19bbd3a10d141bd7bce803/lateximg_large.png","width":938},"regular":{"height":112,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/4fb098bb3d19bbd3a10d141bd7bce803/lateximg.png","width":469}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Therefore, debt-equity ratio should be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Debt-equity ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Total Debt}} {\\text{Total Equity}}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{0.46} {0.54}\\\\ \\\\\n&= \\boxed{0.85}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nIn conclusion, the debt-equity ratio is **0.85**.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":208,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/9bb0bd25e9643ca9284826777d43d53d/lateximg_large.png","width":993},"regular":{"height":104,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/9bb0bd25e9643ca9284826777d43d53d/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Before proceeding with the second requirement, let us define the equity multiplier.\n\n**Equity multiplier** measures a portion of a company's assets financed by shareholders' equity.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Equity multiplier}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Total Assets}} {\\text{Total Shareholders' Equity}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":401,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/282a71e87b920e1f1dc5aa4b0336c700/lateximg_large.png","width":788},"regular":{"height":202,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/282a71e87b920e1f1dc5aa4b0336c700/lateximg.png","width":394}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"Since we have already determined the debt-equity ratio, the equity multiplier can be also computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Equity multiplier}& = 1 + \\text{Debt-equity ratio}\\\\ \\\\\n&=1 + 0.85 \\\\ \\\\\n&=\\boxed{1.85}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nIn conclusion, the equity multiplier is **1.85**.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":274,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/d1606af2b35368f02dacbe84d200ac70/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":139,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/590dcbc762a9c0943a930374ae571f46/d1606af2b35368f02dacbe84d200ac70/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"c9b781ef-ae05-496a-ad74-d6d317f3f712","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":8}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880801,"exerciseName":"6","page":85,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"bc027c55-c071-4e48-ae61-4c62705ae54a","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-questions-and-problems-6-bc027c55-c071-4e48-ae61-4c62705ae54a"},{"id":14880802,"exerciseName":"7","page":85,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"89363d91-ab61-4f07-a0fe-bb47a5a1bdc7","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-questions-and-problems-7-89363d91-ab61-4f07-a0fe-bb47a5a1bdc7"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880799,"exerciseName":"4","page":85,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"37172fa0-9ca6-4d3b-93a9-3a8fa8c4e288","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-fi